[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold] QC gave evidence
[normal]Q68 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Stephen, we are going to crack on because colleagues are very keen to hear the Chancellor’s autumn statement, so we are going to get moving.
[normal] 
[normal]Would you like to say anything to start off
[normal] 
[normal]or jump straight into questions? 
[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold]: Could I make two very brief observations?
[normal] 
[normal]First
[normal],
[normal] I would like to say that I am very strongly supportive of the inquiry that you are undertaking 
[normal]on 
[normal]the possibility of constitutional codification, not least because
[normal],
[normal] whether the conclusion is that that is a good thing or a bad thing, the process of discussing the nature and content of our constitution, the process of considering whether it would be beneficial to move closer to codification, is undoubtedly in the public interest.
[normal] 
[normal]I think that helps to enable everyone—the man in the street and particular groups of individuals—to understand the concepts much better and that has to be a good thing. 
[normal]Secondly, equally briefly, I am particularly supportive, if I may say so, of the idea of concentrating on the role of the judiciary within that overall context.
[normal] 
[normal]It is clear from the evidence that you have already received, which I have looked at, that what that is going to enable you to do is to consider what the status of a codified constitution would be and what its nature would be, how it would fit within our overall system of governance.
[normal] 
[normal]That
[normal],
[normal] I think
[normal],
[normal] too
[normal],
[normal] is very beneficial.
[normal] 
[normal]Until you understand what the status of a codified constitution would be and what it would amount to, it is very difficult to come to a conclusion 
[normal]about 
[normal]whether it is a good idea.
[normal] 
[normal]All in all, as I say, I am very supportive and I feel privileged to be here. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chair:[bold] Thank you, Stephen
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]It is 
[normal]very good that you are here
[normal],
[normal] and thank you for your long-term commitment to working in this field.
[normal] 
[normal]It is very instructive.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q69 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner:[bold] Could you start by giving us a brief overview of the current constitutional role of the judiciary? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold]: Yes.
[normal] 
[normal]I suppose the traditional analysis is that there are three key elements in the constitution: 
[normal]Parliament—
[normal]the legislature
[normal]—
[normal]the Executive
[normal],
[normal] and the judiciary, and that they all have different functions.
[normal] 
[normal]Those functions are well known.
[normal] 
[normal]I think that traditional analysis still holds good.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q70 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner:[bold] Would you mind setting them out, for my benefit and 
[normal]that of 
[normal]others? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold]: Of course.
[normal] 
[normal]Parliament makes the law, the judiciary interpret and apply the law to particular factual positions and the Executive administer and enforce the law.
[normal] 
[normal]That is the way that I would express it
[normal],
[normal] in very simple terms.
[normal]I think there is one interesting 
[normal]modern 
[normal]qualification to that.
[normal] 
[normal]This is something that is still in the course of development.
[normal] 
[normal]What I think has become increasingly recognised is that inevitably judicial decisions, interpreting and applying the law to particular factual situations, involve statements of principle
[normal]. 
[normal]At least
[normal], the
[normal] higher up the judicial hierarchy you go, the more likely it is that you will get a statement of principle.
[normal] 
[normal]That is inevitable and surely appropriate.
[normal] 
[normal]You don’t want judges simply to say, “This is the law that Parliament has made.
[normal] 
[normal]Applying it to the facts
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]I think the 
[normal]answer is X or Y”.
[normal] 
[normal]You want judges to explain their reasons and you want them to articulate the principles that they think are relevant to the case in explaining how they
[normal] 
[normal]are applying the law to the facts.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Once those principles have been articulated by the judges, they become, in themselves, part of our law.
[normal] 
[normal]They are the principles of case law which are then
[normal] 
[normal]applied in later cases.
[normal] 
[normal]That is how our common law has developed.
[normal] 
[normal]I think there is an increasing understanding of the importance of those principles, as established particularly by the higher courts, as forming part of the corpus of law that applies in our country.
[normal] 
[normal]The same is true of any other common law system where judicial decisions have the same importance as they have here.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q71 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner:[bold] Is it that there must be some principles o
[normal]r
[normal] 
[normal]that 
[normal]there should be some principles
[normal] behind what
[normal] 
[normal]lawyers
[normal] are finding? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold]: I think it is inevitable that the judges will set out the principles upon which they make their decisions.
[normal] 
[normal]They could not do their job without doing that.
[normal] 
[normal]Speaking personally, I also think that is a good idea because one of the advantages of judicial decision-making
[normal],
[normal] fr
[normal]o
[normal]m a 
[normal]public interest 
[normal]point of view
[normal],
[normal] is that judges do give reasons for their decisions.
[normal] 
[normal]You can see their principles set out in their decisions
[normal], you can see how
[normal] the judges arrive at those principles, you can critique them and it is entirely transparent. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q72 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner:[bold] In the paper you co-authored with Professor Bogdanor, you stated
[normal],
[normal] “It has become apparent that we have, in a piecemeal and unplanned way, been codifying our constitution”.
[normal] 
[normal]How do you think these piecemeal changes 
[normal]h
[normal]ave affected the judiciary? 
[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold]: A very good example is the way in which our constitution changed between 2003 and 2005.
[normal] 
[normal]That particular change was one 
[normal]that
[normal] directly affected the judiciary and, for example, led to the headship of the judiciary passing from the Lord Chancellor to the Lord Chief Justice.
[normal] 
[normal]It seems to me indisputable that that is an example of our constitution changing in a rather 
[normal]piecemeal and informal way
[normal],
[normal] and in a way 
[normal]that
[normal] many people regarded as not 
[normal]entirely
[normal] satisfactory.
[normal] 
[normal]The outcome may have been very satisfactory.
[normal]The key features of the changes that took place there
[normal],
[normal] including the subdivision of the 
[normal]role of the 
[normal]Lord Chancellor, the setting up of a Supreme Court independent of Parliament, the recognition of the status of the Lord Chief Justice as head of the judiciary, are all substantive changes to the constitution that I suspect most people would applaud, but the process by which it happened has been the subject of a fair bit of criticism.
[normal] 
[normal]One of the 
[normal]benefits 
[normal]of a codified constitution is that change in the future would be much more transparent.
[normal] 
[normal]A codified constitution obviously would not be unchangeable, it would be capable of being amended, but the proce
[normal]ss
[normal] of amendment would be a little more formal than it has 
[normal]been 
[normal]in the past, and therefore more democratic.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q73 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner:[bold] I don’t understand why they are democratic and how they have actually changed.
[normal] 
[normal]I know they had changed but I don’t understand why it was so important that the Lord Chancellor handed over to the senior judge. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold]: Unless you would particularly like me to, I will not dwell on the detail of those changes, but it seems to me that if you disapprove not only of the process by which that happened but of the substantive outcome, there is an even stronger argument in favour of codification.
[normal] 
[normal]The whole problem about that process was that it took place in a slightly less than transparent way.
[normal] 
[normal]By the time Parliament came to approve this in the form of the Constitutional Reform Act, everything was pretty well signed, sealed and delivered.
[normal] 
[normal]There was not the possibility, I suspect, of any real debate at the outset.
[normal] 
[normal]There was no Green Paper or White Paper; there was no formal process.
[normal] 
[normal]It seems to me that someone—I am not one of those; on the contrary, I feel that the outcome was appropriate—who disapproved o
[normal]f
[normal] the outcome
[normal] 
[normal]would be all the more strongly in favour of a slightly more formal and transparent process for achieving constitutional change, and that is what codification would provide.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q74 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] I don’t know whether you caught Lord Judge’s remarks yesterday
[normal], which were
[normal] reported today.
[normal] 
[normal]The
[normal]y
[normal] follow on from Lord Laws, Lord Sumption and Lady Hale, all of whom have raised this issue of European judicial activism
[normal],
[normal] and all seem to infer that if there is clarity about what we can do in terms of the British judiciary, that clarity would help put lines in the sand about how far interpretation on thin
[normal]g
[normal]s like the European Convention o
[normal]f
[normal] Human Rights could 
[normal]g
[normal]o.
[normal] 
[normal]Forgive me if you have not followed that, and I will not p
[normal]u
[normal]rsue it, but if you have followed that debate, what is your view on that?
[normal] 
[normal]Would it be helpful to define British rights within a European context by having them written down and codified? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold]: Unfortunately I was not able to go and listen to Lord Judge’s speech last night and I have not seen a transcript of it yet.
[normal] 
[normal]I have read reports about it in the newspapers.
[normal] 
[normal]I have read the recent speech by Lord Sumption and the recent lecture by Lord Justice Laws.
[normal]Since
[normal] 
[normal]you are inviting me to give my own views, perhaps I might do it in 
[normal]this 
[normal]way
[normal]: 
[normal]I would like to divide this into two parts.
[normal] 
[normal]Part 1 is international and part 2 is domestic.
[normal] 
[normal]I think it is important to start with the international aspect, and I am not sure how far this was covered in some of the speeches that I have mentioned.
[normal] 
[normal]As I see it, the European Convention on Human Rights is an international treaty.
[normal] 
[normal]We have signed up to that; we are parties to it.
[normal] 
[normal]From this perspective it is like any other international treaty, and it contains some provisions, including a provision that says that decisions by the 
[normal]Strasb
[normal]o
[normal]urg Court
[normal] are binding in the particular case that the court has been considering.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In theory
[normal],
[normal] we could decide at some point in time to leave the Convention and to cease to be bound by that treaty, but as long as we are bound by the treaty
[normal],
[normal] I think it is extremely important that we uphold its provisions and conform to decisions of the court in particular cases.
[normal] 
[normal]That is because
[normal],
[normal] if we decide to ignore the provisions of treaties by which we are bound, we can expect other countries to do the same.
[normal] 
[normal]It would set, in my view, an appalling precedent if other countries refused to extradite people to this country even though there is an extradition treaty, or if trade arrangements were routinely ignored.
[normal] 
[normal]We simply have to comply with our international obligations.
[normal] 
[normal]I think that is a point worth making.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Let me move to the second part.
[normal] 
[normal]I realise Mr Turner wants to question me on the first part but let me just make my second point.
[normal] 
[normal]Domestically
[normal],
[normal] the situation is different.
[normal] W
[normal]e have incorporated the Convention into domestic law
[normal],
[normal] using the mechanism of the Human Rights Act.
[normal] 
[normal]The Human Rights Act provides that our courts have to take into account the decisions of the 
[normal]Strasb
[normal]o
[normal]urg Court
[normal] in deciding other cases, but they do not have to regard themselves as bound.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Lord Bingham
[normal]—
[normal]who as you know presided over the judiciary committee of the House of Lords for the first 10 years or so of the existence of the Human Rights Act and who is widely regarded as having made an extraordinary contribution as one of our senior judges—expressed the view in more than one case, with the support of the other 
[normal]L
[normal]aw
[normal] L
[normal]ords, that generally speaking we should follow decisions of the Strasb
[normal]o
[normal]urg Court.
[normal] 
[normal]He did not consider it right for the higher courts in this country to take a significantly independent line.
[normal] M
[normal]ore recently, as, Chairman, you have pointed out, other 
[normal]judges
[normal] have taken the view that we 
[normal]should 
[normal]take a more independent line, frankly reflecting public and political opinion in so saying.
[normal] 
[normal]There is nothing in the Human Rights Act that prevents 
[normal]judges 
[normal]from doing that, because the Act simply says you must take into account 
[normal]Strasb
[normal]o
[normal]urg
[normal] decisions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It seems to me that what we are witnessing is an evolution in judiciary thinking.
[normal] 
[normal]We are witnessing the principles, which I mentioned in an earlier answer, evolving and being adjusted to take into account prevailing soci
[normal]o
[normal]-political circumstances, and that is one of the strength
[normal]s
[normal] of the common law.
[normal] 
[normal]I see no problem with that, but what is important for prese
[normal]n
[normal]t purposes, in answer, Chairman, to your question, is that none of this, to my mind, undermines the notion that 
[normal]we 
[normal]should continue to be bound by the Convention as a matter of treaty obligation.
[normal] 
[normal]None of it undermines the concept of enforcing the Convention in this country through the Human Rights Act.
[normal] 
[normal]What it means is that we may choose to apply the Convention in this country in a way 
[normal]that
[normal] is different from the way in which the 
[normal]Strasb
[normal]o
[normal]urg Court
[normal] has recommended.
[normal] 
[normal]That is permissible under the Act and looks as if it is likely to happen more and more.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q75 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Lord Judge apparently said last night—and again I am going by reports
[normal],
[normal] not the transcript—that the British courts had supremacy over 
[normal]Strasb
[normal]o
[normal]urg
[normal] and should retain that supremacy.
[normal] 
[normal]I think there are many people in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] who
[normal]—
[normal]in the con
[normal]text 
[normal]of
[normal] the acceptance of
[normal] human rights standards of course
[normal]—
[normal]would be reassured if that was not a debating point but was written down so that everyone could feel at ease with our own judiciary and not a sense of unease 
[normal]at 
[normal]judicial activism.
[normal] 
[normal]This is a matter of there will never be certainty
[normal],
[normal] but there can be a degree of clarification, which is where I am leading you, in a sense.
[normal] 
[normal]Clarification is helpful to all of us in these circumstances. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold]: I accept that.
[normal] 
[normal]Putting the point that you have made to me in slightly different words
[normal],
[normal] and in the context of constitutional codification, what you might seek to achieve in codifying
[normal] 
[normal]the constitution in this area—not in changing it
[normal],
[normal] but in codifying it and in clarifying it—would be to incorporate the Human Rights Act into 
[normal]it 
[normal]but
[normal],
[normal] to put what I have just been saying in even clearer terms
[normal],
[normal] to make it absolutely explicit that
[normal],
[normal] in the general run of cases
[normal],
[normal] the decision
[normal]s were
[normal] for our courts to make, that the application of the Convention was for our courts.
[normal] 
[normal]If, for instance, although I personally would not agree with this, our courts took the view that it was 
[normal]consistent with
[normal] the 
[normal]Convention to deny prisoners votes, then our courts would be entitled to say that.
[normal] 
[normal]If in the end our courts thought that the Convention permitted that, they would be entitled to make that ruling.
[normal]If a codified constitution were to make that explicit, I agree with you that that would be an
[normal] 
[normal]additional benefit of codification.
[normal] 
[normal]The only qualification to all of that is that
[normal],
[normal] as long as we are parties to the Convention, as long as we are bound as a matter of international law by the Convention
[normal], then i
[normal]n an individual 
[normal]case, 
[normal]if the 
[normal]Strasb
[normal]o
[normal]urg Court
[normal] makes a ruling, we have to accept its authority.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q76 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] If my colleagues will forgive me, I have missed the last two meetings on this and they may have covered this already, but my understanding in 
[normal]r
[normal]esp
[normal]ec
