[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q80 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] It is a very helpful diversion, in many ways
[normal],
[normal] because I was not asking you about the policy.
[normal] 
[normal]I think that was a matter of politics and elected people should decide those things.
[normal] 
[normal]I am not involved in one side or the other on a particular case.
[normal] 
[normal]We all have strong views about particular cases, of course.
[normal] 
[normal]My point was more about clarity, the fact that I don’t know, Mr Turner does not know, the man and woman in the street sometimes don’t know, 
[normal]and 
[normal]that trying to make these things more transparent allows us to have a proper political debate.
[normal] 
[normal]At the moment there are 20 different interpretations, for example on prisoners’ rights.
[normal] 
[normal]There are thousands of different views on this.
[normal] 
[normal]While you can never have certainty, to have a degree of clarity
[normal]—my 
[normal]view that I am putting to you 
[normal]is 
[normal]that the more clarity there is
[normal],
[normal] the easier it is for us to make decisions and to understand the consequences of those decisions. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stephen Hockman[bold]: I would agree with that.
[normal] 
[normal]Can I just say again, brin
[normal]g
[normal]ing out the implications of what you have just said, in relation to the discussion that Mr Turner and I were just having, one of the things that a codified constitution probably ought to clarify—and until we had this discussion I do not think I was clear in my own mind about it as I am now—the relationship between our international obligations on the one hand and binding domestic law on the other.
[normal] 
[normal]This is an area which it seems to me 
[normal]is 
