[normal]              
[normal]Did you
[normal] 
[normal]want to say anything to kick u
[normal]s
[normal] off or are you happy to jump straight into questions? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: Let’s just go straight to questions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q90 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner:[bold] Could you briefly describe the role of the judiciary in the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s 
[normal]current constitutional arrangements? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: The current role of the judiciary in judicial reviews is essentially ensuring that Central 
[normal]a
[normal]nd Local Government and public bodies act within the powers conferred on them by Parliament.
[normal] 
[normal]That is filtered through the judges’ idea of the rule of law, rather as the previous witness was describing.
[normal] 
[normal]The best short formulation of what it seems to me the judiciary in general thinks about this is in Lord Bingham’s book on the rule of law, where he says, and this is how the rule of law app
[normal]l
[normal]ies to this particular context
[normal],
[normal] “Ministers and public officers at all levels must exercise the powers conferred on them in good faith, fairly, for the purpose for which the powers were conferred, without exceeding the limits of such powers and not unreasonably.”
[normal] 
[normal]That is a general statement of what one imagines is going through the judiciary’s mind when they are making decisions in these cases.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q91 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner:[bold] One of our witnesses, Dr Elliott, drew a distinction between a flat and a hierarchical constitution.
[normal] 
[normal]Which is more appropriate to the 
[normal]UK
[normal]? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: I use a different language 
[normal]from 
[normal]that.
[normal] 
[normal]If we are talking about some form of codification, there are two possible methods.
[normal] 
[normal]One is to go back to the drawing board and write something like the new South Africa
[normal]n
[normal] 
[normal]constitution 
[normal]of 20 years ago, where effectively we reform the state and lay
[normal] 
[normal]out in great detail the powers of different 
[normal]organs 
[normal]of state and how they relate to each other and so on.
[normal]The second approach is to gather exi
[normal]s
[normal]ting constitutional material into one place, metaphorically 
[normal]in 
[normal]a large, leather-bound volume, and label that material as being constitutional.
[normal] 
[normal]There are some quite significant practical problems with that.
[normal] 
[normal]I think we all know what the major constitutional statutes are, but there are lots of things of constitutional importance that are buried in other statutes.
[normal] 
[normal]There is lots of non-statutory material, the 
[normal]Cabinet Manual
[normal], for example,
[normal] and to what extent is
[normal] that part of the constitution, and there are lots of arrangements that are purely customary.
[normal] 
[normal]That is a practical difficulty.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Going on from that, the idea that judges might get involved in assessing the validity of primary legislation against some constitution I think is a separate issue to that of codification.
[normal] 
[normal]The best example of that is in 
[normal]Israel
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Israel
[normal] has no codified constitution
[normal],
[normal] but a practice has developed whereby their legislature labels or certifies some laws as being constitutional and,
[normal] 
[normal]should there be a conflict, the Israeli courts will then give primacy to those constitutional or so-called basic laws over other laws.
[normal] 
[normal]That is an example on the one hand.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]O
[normal]n the other hand we have the Dutch constitution, which although it is codified in the conventional sense and all
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]rules laid out, it specifically forbids the judiciary from opining on the validity of primary legislation.
[normal] 
[normal]These two issues, although often wrapped into one, I think are in principle separate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q92 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner:[bold] If the 
[normal]UK
[normal] adopted a codified constitution, would that give it a higher status or not? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: I think there are two or three different things that could happen.
[normal] 
[normal]The simplest thing that Parliament could do 
[normal]is 
[normal]to do what happens in 
[normal]Israel
[normal] and say that from now on we are going to label certain laws as being constitutional laws, which does not happen at the moment.
[normal] 
[normal]All laws, once passed, are the same, at least in theory.
[normal] 
[normal]If that happens, the judiciary would no doubt, over time as cases came to them—because of course an important point with understanding judicial 
[normal]review is its haphazard nature.
[normal] 
[normal]It is not as if the judges can wake up and decide to go and review something that they do not like the look of.
[normal] 
[normal]They have to wait for an applicant and a ju
[normal]st
[normal]iciable issue and a case.
[normal]That would be the simplest thing.
[normal] 
[normal]Effectively collecting together some laws currently on the statute book and calling them constitutional would over time have the same effect, because very likely the judges would take notice of that.
[normal] 
[normal]If you had a fully codified constitution and it was a new constitution along the lines that most countries have, that constitution would have rules in it about the circumstances in which judges could review legislation, or indeed it might not have such rules, because
[normal],
[normal] contrary to what is generally believed, the 
[normal]US
[normal] constitution does not provide for judicia
[normal]l
[normal] review.
[normal] 
[normal]The role that the Supreme Court took on, going back to Marb
[normal]u
[normal]ry v 
[normal]Madison
[normal], which is the famous case at the beginning of the 19th century, was to adopt for themselves this power to review legislation.
[normal] 
[normal]It is not in the constitution.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A rather similar case more recently 
[normal]wa
[normal]s in Denmark.
[normal] 
[normal]The Danish constitution says nothing about judicial review but the Danish courts ha
[normal]ve
[normal] started in practice to review legislation in that 
[normal]US
[normal] sort of way.
[normal] 
[normal]There are no hard answers to any of these questions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q93 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Turner:[bold] I think I heard you say the judges cannot wake up one morning and decide to look at this.
[normal] 
[normal]They can only do so if somebody else has tried to change the law.
[normal] 
[normal]Is there anything that prevents them from doing so? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: Judges in our jurisdiction, and it is the same in the 
[normal]US
[normal], only get to hear cases if an 
[normal]appellant
[normal] brings a case to them.
[normal] 
[normal]The judiciary cannot create its own cases.
[normal]We have a different situation in the minority of countries that have proper constitutional courts, i.e. 
[normal]the
[normal] Austrian model, where there is a 
[normal]specific
[normal] court, as we were hearing earlier, which does not try normal cases.
[normal] 
[normal]Its role is to opine on the constitutionality of all new legislation, but that is quite unusual and certainly very far from where we are in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] at the moment.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q94 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Fabian Hamilton:[bold] Mr Le Roux, Professor Le Sueur told us that were the UK to adopt a codified constitution, he
[normal],
[normal] “
[normal]w
[normal]ould like to see the preservation of the principle of Parliamentary supremacy so our elected representatives in Parliament would have the final say on the content of legislation, rather than constitutional supremacy in which a judicial body would have a veto on unconstitutional legislation.”
[normal] 
[normal]I wondered what your view was. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: I think it is rather difficult and it is made more difficult by the fact that there is not very much consensus at the moment, as far as I can see, as to what the exact relationship between the role of the judiciary and Parliament’s role is.
[normal] 
[normal]You hear some extreme statements, which most people 
[normal]would 
[normal]say were incorrect.
[normal] 
[normal]We had the view of two judges, famously in the 
[normal]Jackson
[normal] case a few years ago
[normal],
[normal] to the effect that parliamentary sovereignty is a creation of the common law.
[normal] 
[normal]In other words, in extreme circumstances the Supreme Court can strike down legislation.
[normal] 
[normal]Probably the majority of judges do not think that.
[normal] 
[normal]We don’t know
[normal];
[normal] we only have these two judges who said that.
[normal]On the other hand you sometimes hear the view, perhaps from Members of this House, that Parliament can legislate as it likes without restriction.
[normal] 
[normal]If you
[normal] 
[normal]examine that, a number of questions come up.
[normal] 
[normal]The first point that I would 
[normal]make 
[normal]is 
[normal]that 
[normal]there are clearly practical restrictions on Parliament’s ability to legislate as it 
[normal]would 
[normal]like.
[normal] 
[normal]It would be rather difficult, to reverse Scottish devolution at this stage
[normal],
[normal] in practice.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q95 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Fabian [bold]Hamilton[bold]:[bold] It is technically possible, isn’t it? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: Indeed.
[normal] 
[normal]It is technically possible for the British Parliament to decide that 
[normal]Canada
[normal]’s independence is to be withdrawn.
[normal] 
[normal]What would follow from that
[normal],
[normal] one may ask.
[normal] 
[normal]I think you are asking 
[normal]whether 
[normal]there 
[normal]are 
[normal]also legal or normative restrictions on parliamentary sovereignty, and here we get into much more contested territory.
[normal] 
[normal]Going back to the previous discussion, I think most people would say that the 
[normal]UK
[normal] does have obligations under international law that Parliament cannot vary in the context of international law.
[normal] 
[normal]For example, Parliament might take the view that embarking on a particular war was a legal and proper thing to do, but that would not, at an international level, prevent that war 
[normal]from 
[normal]being held to be illegal.
[normal]The question that I always ask people, to pin them down when the
[normal]y
[normal] express a strong support for parliamentary sovereignty, is
[normal],
[normal] do they believe that citizens have rights 
[normal]that
[normal] Parliament cannot take away, or do they not believe that
[normal]? 
[normal]The logic of the position is that 
[normal]t
[normal]hey must believe that citizens have at least one right, which is the right to vote.
[normal] 
[normal]The whole intellectual underpinning of the modern doctrine of parliamentary sovereignty is democratic legitimacy.
[normal] 
[normal]It was not so in the 19
[normal]th
[normal] century.
[normal] 
[normal]Indeed, most people, when asked the question in a neutral way, would say that they did have rights which Parliament could not or ought not to be able to take away.
[normal] 
[normal]There is no way you can go away and look up the answer to this question.
[normal] 
[normal]What we see in all of these situations is just a reflection of the general view mutating over time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Coming to the particular issue here, who owns the rule of law?
[normal] 
[normal]Is there some higher principle of the rule of law which in certain circumstances might 
[normal]t
[normal]rump
[normal] parliamentary 
[normal]sovereignty?
[normal] 
[normal]The difficulty there is that the judges and Parliament, or the Government, might have different views about what the rule of law meant in certain particular circumstances.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Going back to our recent 
[normal]e
[normal]vents, the practical question here is if Parliament were to introduce primary legislation 
[normal]that
[normal] the judges believed to be contrary to the rule of law
[normal],
[normal] as they understood it, what would they do about it
[normal]? 
[normal]That is the particular difficulty we might be confronting at the moment with the current Government consultation exercise.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q96 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Fabian [bold]Hamilton[bold]:[bold] We have discussed already this morning, 
[normal]and you, in reply
[normal] to Mr Turner, 
[normal]mentioned 
[normal]judicial review and some of the processes in the 
[normal]UK
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]I wonder how judicial review here differs from countries where there is a codified constitution. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: A
[normal]s
[normal] I 
[normal]understand
[normal] it, the great majority, probably all countries which are essentially democratic, rule
[normal]-
[normal]of
[normal]-
[normal]law jurisdictions, have some form of judicial review whereby appellants can go to the court and say, “This official has acted beyond his appropriate powers or he has behaved unfairly”.
[normal] 
[normal]How likely those applications are to succeed is another matter.
[normal] 
[normal]I think I am right in saying that in 
[normal]Singapore
[normal], in the whole history of the republic, there has been no successful application for judicial review despite the fact that that process exists in principle.
[normal] 
[normal]That form of judicial review against the actions of officials is quite general.
[normal] 
[normal]The other sort of judicial review, which is judicial review of legislation, can only happen if there is some higher benchmark against which to judge its legitimacy.
[normal] 
[normal]That higher benchmark normally in most states is a codified constitution.
[normal] 
[normal]As I said earlier, it does not need to be.
[normal] 
[normal]In the case of 
[normal]Israel
[normal] we just have two different sorts of law, which have different priority.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q97 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Paul Flynn:[bold] On the question of irreversible changes taking place, I recall that Enoch Powell went to see Prime Minister Winston Churchill and urged him to re
[normal]-
[normal]col
[normal]on
[normal]ise 
[normal]India
[normal], so there are people who do have ambitions to change what to most of us would seem irreversible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]Could we take up a point made by our previous witness in saying that he did not think we would achieve a codified constitution
[normal],
[normal] but it is benefi
[normal]cial
[normal], certainly education
[normal]al
[normal] to MPs, to discuss this and to consider the consequence of it?
[normal] 
[normal]What is your view?
[normal] 
[normal]Are we going to get there? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: If you look at international comparators, when countries come up with brand new constitutions it is in the context of some sort of general political crisis 
[normal]that
[normal] requires a reformation of the state, in other words a change from one regime to another or the 
[normal]granting
[normal] of independence of the settlement of a civil war of something of that nature.
[normal] 
[normal]South Africa
[normal] is a good example.
[normal] 
[normal]I would rephrase the question and ask how likely it is that something like that is going to happen in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] in the foreseeable future.
[normal] 
[normal]It is probably unlikely, although Scottish independence, if it happened, might just be such an event, so it is not to be completely ruled out.
[normal]In the absence of that, is anything in the codification direction very likely to happen?
[normal] 
[normal]I think there is some merit in assembling the obvious constitutional legislation and putting a big constitution label on the cover.
[normal] 
[normal]How far that takes us I am not sure.
[normal] 
[normal]The change that I would like to see, and I have argued this before this Committee before, is a much simpler one, where Parliament itself simply starts labelling, when appropriate, new laws as being constitutional.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q98 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Paul Flynn:[bold] Lord Lester last week resisted the idea that 
[normal]Parliaments here 
[normal]of all parties have become more willing to release power through the devolution process to 
[normal]Scotland
[normal], 
[normal]Wales
[normal] and 
[normal]Northern Ireland
[normal] and to 
[normal]Europe
[normal] as well.
[normal] 
[normal]He gave an example of that
[normal]—
[normal]possibly that is not going on
[normal]—
[normal]that Parliament is as power 
[normal]re
[normal]tentive as ever.
[normal] 
[normal]He used the example of prisoners’ rights to vote.
[normal] 
[normal]Do you find that the process is going on and it is a sl
[normal]ip
[normal]pery slope and that it will continue and that power will be devolved from Parliament in the way that it has been over the last 20 years? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: It is a complex question because several different things seem to me to be happening at once.
[normal] 
[normal]One thing, as you say, is it is in line with Britain’s relative decline in the world and the process of accession to the EU that Parliament has 
[normal]sacrificed
[normal], in practice if not in theory, an area of authority to other jurisdiction.
[normal] 
[normal]It has also sacrificed authority within the 
[normal]UK
[normal] to other jurisdictions through the process of devolution.
[normal]In the core area, over which Parliament still appears to have an untrammelled authority, there are further difficulties, again referred to in previous evidence
[normal],
[normal] trying to pin down what the extent of that 
[normal]sovereignty
[normal] is, when the courts are becoming perhaps more assertive in talking about principles rather than simply the interpretation of legislation.
[normal] 
[normal]I think that in turn reflects a general decay in relations between the law and Parliament that has been going on for some time.
[normal] 
[normal]Some of that is just the general siloing of 
[normal]elites
[normal] 
[normal]that
[normal] seems to have occurred over the last 50 years or more.
[normal] 
[normal]At one time, 
[normal]the
[normal] mythical golden age, there were quite a lot of MPs who worked as QCs in the morning and then came to Parliament in the afternoon.
[normal] 
[normal]Those people existed but there aren’t very many of them anymore.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I think a significant event in that process of breakdown of relationships was the Constitutional Reform Act of 2005, which, on paper, looked quite sensible because it removed this rather anomalous position of the Lord Chancellor and seemed to be a move towards the 
[normal]full
[normal] separation of powers which would be normal in most countries.
[normal] 
[normal]But 
[normal]the effect
[normal] of it was further breakdown in communication, I believe, because
[normal] of
[normal] this rather odd position that the Lord Chancellor had was an important link between the legislature and the judiciary and a safety valve when things went wrong.
[normal] 
[normal]Now the Lord Chancellor is just another Minister who is not even a lawyer at the moment.
[normal] 
[normal]At the same time, 
[normal]the 
[normal]senior judiciary, while they are still on the bench, no longer sit in the Lords, although they come back afterwards.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]At one time, and this is carica
[normal]t
[normal]u
[normal]ri
[normal]ng it slightly, this country was run by an establishment of people who might have gone to the same schools and had similar ideas about how things ought to work, and a lot of that was never written down in any formal way.
[normal] 
[normal]Those understandings, for good or ill, are breaking down.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q99 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Paul Flynn:[bold] I am sure you are encouraged, as we are, b
[normal]y
[normal] the evidence of increased public interest in a codified constitution
[normal]: what
[normal] has happened behind you since you started to speak.
[normal] 
[normal]A final question: how would the current model for judicial review in the 
[normal]United Kingdom
[normal] be likely to change if a codified constitution was adopted? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: I think, as we were saying earlier, it would very much depend what that codified constitution was.
[normal] 
[normal]The mere effect of labelling some legislation as being constitutional, even if it is existing 
[normal]legislation
[normal], opens the doors for the court to review other legislation against it, and I think that 
[normal]t
[normal]hat would happen.
[normal] 
[normal]If we were to go the full
[normal]-blown
[normal] new constitution route, I think it would be sensible for that constitution to say something about what the role of the judiciary ought to be.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q100 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Fabian [bold]Hamilton[bold]:[bold] Thank you, Nat.
[normal] 
[normal]Is there anything that you would like to say, anything left unsaid?
[normal] 
[normal]This is your moment? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Nat Le Roux[bold]: Just at the risk of advertising our own activities, I will go back to the seminar that you were not able to attend, Chairman.
[normal] 
[normal]Something that is going on at the moment that is highly relevant to 
[normal]t
[normal]his is the Government consultation exercise on 
[normal]the 
[normal]scope of judicial review.
[normal] 
[normal]Some of that is about administrative tidying up and efficiency and is uncontroversial, but some of it is not.
[normal] 
[normal]Two proposals particularly are, I think, worrying in their implications.
[normal] 
[normal]One is the on the question of standing.
[normal] 
[normal]At the moment, even an unaffected party may apply for judicial review if there is a public interest involved.
[normal] 
[normal]The people who make these applications are typically NGOs.
[normal] 
[normal]The suggestion in the consultation exercise is that that should be stopped.
[normal] 
[normal]In other words, someone has to have a direct interest where they have been personally affected before they may apply.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]At the same time there is another proposal in the consultation exercise whereby protective costs orders—the orders that immunise the applicant from picking up the defence costs, the Government costs, if he loses—should only be available if people do not have a direct interest.
[normal] 
[normal]You can see how the combined effect of those two measures would very severely reduce the set of people who were ever capable of applying for judicial review.
[normal] 
[normal]They would have to be wealthy people with a direct interest.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What is the reaction of the judiciary going to be if these measures are introduced?
[normal] 
[normal]It is far from certain that they will go along with it.
[normal] 
[normal]They may take the view that in this particular instance there is a higher principle of ru
[normal]l
[normal]e of law that they will use as a way of, in effect, not accepting this.
[normal] 
[normal]We have had other examples of that in the past where 
[normal]ouster
[normal] clauses in legislation—a clause in a statute that says the courts may not review the validity of this act or the legality of this action—have been politely ignored by the judges.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This comes back to the question not what is the truth of it, because the truth of it is what people believe.
[normal] 
[normal]What do judges believe
[normal]—
[normal]that they are guardians of something called the rule of law, which sits separate to the authority of Parliament?
[normal] 
[normal]I personally believe it is the proposition that is best not tested.
[normal] 
[normal]If these Government proposals go ahead it is going to be tested.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chair:[bold] That is very thought provoking.
